We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Create an Inventory Committee composed of adequate number of members to be able to complete the physical inventory in three months or less. The Inventory Committee shall have at least one member each from the Accounting and Property Divisions/Unit of the agency who shall have the following functions among others: 

a.	Reconcile differences between the physical inventory report and the general ledger balance of each PPE account. Subsequently, the Accountant shall identify if the difference represents PPE that are still existing, no longer existing but with pertinent records; 

b.	Complete the conduct of annual physical inventory and make updates on the current/ existing inventory reports, and to adhere with the timeline of activities under the Physical Inventory Plan (PIP). The Inventory Committee and accounting office shall compare the latest Report on the RPCPPE/Inventory Report with the PPE Ledger Cards (PPELCs);

c.	Prepare a list of PPE items which are recorded in the PPELCs but not included in the RPCPPE/Physical Inventory Report as well as PPE items which are included in the RPCPPE but not recorded in the PPELCs; and

d.	After the completion of physical count, for the PPEs classified as non- existing/ missing and of those without available records of accountability, the management should conduct the procedures enumerated under Items 7 and 8 of the same COA Circular for the disposition and derecognition.

We recommended that Management undertake the following courses of action:

a. For the Local Chief Executive to create an Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of the Road Networks;

b. For the department heads who are core part of the Inventory Committee to designate capable alternates to conduct the physical inventory of road networks;

c. For the Municipal Engineer to spearhead the physical inventory of the road networks because of his technical knowledge and skills in engineering; 

d. For the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer (in lieu of the GSO) with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

e. For the Municipal Treasurer (in lieu of the GSO) to maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map, and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components using the format prescribed under COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 23, 2015; and

f. For the Municipal Accountant to maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network using the prescribed format as mentioned in the above circular and disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the total road network system.

We reiterated our previous recommendation to Management to adopt the use of ATM in the payment of salaries, wages, bonuses and other personnel benefits in order to:

a. Strengthen the internal control system in the Treasury Office;

b. Eliminate possible risk of theft or rubbery during personal withdrawals in bank for payroll funds;

c. Reduce the workload and time spent in preparation of pay envelopes; and

d. Eliminate risk of human error in the distribution of pay envelopes

We recommended that:

the Municipal Accountant record the book reconciling items pertaining to unrecorded deposit/fund transfers, unrecorded withdrawals, and erroneous posting totaling ₱85,459.05 in absolute value;

the Municipal Accountant revert to Cash in Bank- LCCA account and recognize the liability for the equivalent amount of stale checks totaling ₱27,768.00 in compliance with Item 2 of Section 59, Volume I of NGAS Manual for LGUs;

if the checks are about to be considered as stale, the Municipal Treasurer send written notice to the payee on the existence of the check one month before the check becomes stale; and

If the check is already stale at the hands of the payee and presented for replacement, cancel the check on its face and shall be presented on the RCI after the last check issued for the period indicated in the report, and issue a replacement check accordingly.

Observe the proper conduct of annual physical count to come up with a complete and reliable Report of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment;
Prepare and maintain Property Cards for all the agency properties and reconcile with the Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards of the Accounting Office;

Prepare the required reports such as Inventory Count Form, and Physical Inventory Plan (PIP);

Undertake the full disposal proceedings and derecognize unserviceable properties from the accounting books and property records upon disposal thereof based on the approved IIRUP; and

Pursue the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to finally establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We reiterate our previous recommendation for:
The Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) through the BAC Secretariat ensures that all pre-bidding documents are first secured before starting any procurement activity;
The Municipal Accountant to ensure that disbursements are supported with complete documents before effecting payment;
The Municipal Engineer to prepare documents relative to the project, such as but not limited to Program of Work and Statement of Work Accomplished;
The immediate submission of the required documents for post-audit purposes and subsequent inspection thereof.

To address these deficiencies and to facilitate the generation of accurate and timely reports, we recommend the following:
Transition to a fully automated accounting system that encompasses the general ledger, subsidiary ledger, and financial statement preparation to minimize manual work and reduce human errors;
Implement user authentication controls that require login credentials with various access levels (e.g., administrator, encoder, viewer) to prevent unauthorized modifications.
Enable audit logs to monitor all transactions, modifications, and deletions for accountability and data integrity;
Establish automatic backup procedures on a regular schedule to avoid data loss in the event of system failures;
Synchronize data in real-time across all computers to eliminate manual consolidation;
Restrict the deletion of records by requiring formal approval and proper adjustment entries instead of outright deletions; and
Ensure that the accounting system can receive automatic updates to comply with COA regulations and government accounting standards.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that Management oversee the adherence to the pertinent provisions of NGAS Manual for LGUs and applicable policies and guidelines on the accounting and management of inventory to ensure the reliability and fair presentation of the balances in the financial statements.
In particular, we recommended that Management direct:
The Inventory Committee to undertake physical inventory every six months, and prepare and submit the Report of Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI). The resulting RPCI should be reconciled with the property and accounting records to come up with the reliable balances of Inventory accounts;
The Municipal Accountant to institute measures to ensure that inventory items received as donation are properly recorded and accounted for in the books;
The GSO and Accounting Office to properly maintain SCs and SLCs, respectively, for all inventory items to facilitate the review, physical count, and reconciliation of inventories. Thereafter, conduct periodic reconciliation of balances between records;
The GSO to prepare the SSMI as prescribed in NGAS Manual for LGUs. Upon receipt of the report, the Accounting Office shall fill up the unit cost and total cost in the SSMI, which will serve as the basis for recording the expenditure in the books; and
The Municipal Health Officer and heads of all other concerned departments who are receiving goods-in-kind from National Government Agencies or from any source, to inform and coordinate with the GSO of such goods, before issuance to the concerned department or end-user. The GSO shall thereafter furnish the accounting department the necessary documents on the receipt and issuance for proper recording in the books of accounts.
Further, based on the results of this assessment, we also recommended that Management consider endorsing to the SB the creation of a full-fledged MGSO plantilla position to institutionalize inventory management and related functions, ensuring greater efficiency in the delivery of public services.

We recommended that Management:
Coordinate with the Department of Social Welfare and Development Field Office II (DSWD FOII) to facilitate the immediate reconciliation of records and resolution of the noted discrepancy;
Establish regular coordination and communication with the source agency to monitor the status of submitted liquidation reports and ensure timely feedback or validation of fund utilization;
Conduct periodic reconciliation of the Due to National Government Agencies account, particularly for inter-agency fund transfers, to ensure that balances reported in the financial statements are accurate, updated, and supported by verified documentation; and
Review and strengthen internal procedures for monitoring fund utilization and liquidation submissions, including proper documentation, timely reporting, and clear accountability measures.

Considering that our previous recommendations on the same issues were not complied with, the Audit Team reiterated its recommendation that the Local Chief Executive direct the Accountable Officers to:
